 ‘culture’ were formed and negotiated in missionary encounters, and how the social and semiotic possibilities of Christianity lead to a new politic of equal rights in South India. Skillfully combining archival research with anthropological fieldwork, this book examines the full cultural impact of Christianity on Indian religious, social and political life. Connecting historical ethnography to the preoccupations of priests and Jesuit social activists, Mosse throws new light on the contemporary nature of caste, conversion, religious synthesis, secularization, dalit politics, the inherent tensions of religious pluralism, and the struggle for recognition among subordinated people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCastexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aChristianity and other religions. 0aChristianityzIndia, South. 0aSocial classeszIndia, SouthxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  abooks for history lovers.  acaste system in india.  acatholicism.  achristian church.  adiscussion books.  aeasy to read.  aengaging.  aevolution of christianity.  agod and religion.  ahinduism.  ahistory of christianity.  ahistory of religion.  ahome school history books.  aindian religion.  ainformative books.  aleisure reads.  anonfiction books.  apass on books.  apolitical.  areligion and culture.  areligion and politics.  areligion history and culture.  areligious studies.  asouth indian history.  awhat is christianity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027349840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095397040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953970423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520953970/origin